        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request spectral averaging of 8 channels. This will lead to a velocity resolution of 4.7 km/s, more than sufficient to resolve the expected spectral line (expected width: ~100-200 km/s, but smaller linewidths are possible). At a redshift of z=6.595 the [CII] line is shifted to 250.2367 GHz, which is adequately covered by our setup: We place the [CII] line in the upper sideband, and center the precise Lyman Alpha redshift between spw3 and spw4 (with significant overlap between the two), to maximize velocity coverage around the [CII] line in case the offset between the Lyman alpha and the [CII] line is larger than expected. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>As extensivly discussed in the proposal, and verified by our simulations (Fig. 3), observations in ALMA's most compact configuration (36-1) are essential to reach our science goals.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our re-reduction of the cycle 0 observations resulted in a tentative 3.6 sigma (~67 uJy) detection of Himiko in the continuum. With the current setup we will detect this continuum emission at high signficance. As explained in the main proposal, our array choice will sample the short spacing sufficiently, thus a significantly higher continuum flux is expected. Likewise, we expect to detect the [CII] line in these compact-configuration observations with a peak line flux of ~0.5 mJy.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
