    <prp:abstract>The ALMA [CII]/dust non-detection of the bright, highly (~100 Msun/yr) star forming galaxy Himiko at redshift z=6.6 is one of the biggest observational puzzles in early ALMA studies. However, the ALMA cycle 0 observations lack sufficient sampling of short spacings required to image the known extension of Himiko (max linear extent: ~3"). Currently scheduled cycle 1 observations of Himiko using even longer baselines will not change this situation. What is urgently needed are compact configuration observations, that will probe the relevant spatial scales that have been missed so far, as confirmed by our extensive simulations. Our observations are designed to detect [CII] and the underlying dust emission in this key source, and confirm our tentative 3.6 sigma continuum detection that we obtained by re-reducing the cycle 0 archival data at high S/N.  The Himiko results have achieved an important status in the community and thus obtaining an unequivocal answer on the [CII] and dust emission from this key source is imperative.</prp:abstract>
